<ul>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant init</code> â€“ Initialize Vagrant with a Vagrantfile and ./.vagrant directory, using no specified base image. Beforeyou can do vagrant up, youâ€™ll need to specify a base image in the Vagrantfile.</li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant init</code> â€“ Initialize Vagrant with a specific box. To find a box, go to the public Vagrant box catalog. When you find one you like, just replace itâ€™s name with boxpath. For example, vagrant init ubuntu/trusty64.</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="starting-a-vm">Starting a VM</h3>
<ul>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant up</code> â€“ starts vagrant environment (also provisions only on the FIRST vagrant up)</li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant resume</code> â€“ resume a suspended machine (vagrant up works just fine for this as well)</li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant provision</code> â€“ forces reprovisioning of the vagrant machine</li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant reload</code> â€“ restarts vagrant machine, loads new Vagrantfile configuration</li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant reload --provision</code> â€“ restart the virtual machine and force provisioning</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="getting-into-a-vm">Getting into a VM</h3>
<ul>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant ssh</code> â€“ connects to machine via SSH</li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant ssh</code> â€“ If you give your box a name in your Vagrantfile, you can ssh into it with boxname. Works from any directory.</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="stopping-a-vm">Stopping a VM</h3>
<ul>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant halt</code> â€“ stops the vagrant machine</li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant suspend</code> â€“ suspends a virtual machine (remembers state)</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="cleaning-up-a-vm">Cleaning Up a VM</h3>
<ul>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant destroy</code> â€“ stops and deletes all traces of the vagrant machine</li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant destroy -f</code> â€“ same as above, without confirmation</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="boxes">Boxes</h3>
<ul>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant box list</code> â€“ see a list of all installed boxes on your computer</li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant box add</code> â€“ download a box image to your computer</li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant box outdated</code> â€“ check for updates vagrant box update</li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant boxes remove</code> â€“ deletes a box from the machine</li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant package</code> â€“ packages a running virtualbox env in a reusable box</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="saving-progress">Saving Progress</h3>

<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">-vagrant snapshot save [options] [vm-name]</code> â€“ vm-name is often default. Allows us to save so that we can rollback at a later time</p>

<h3 id="tips">Tips</h3>
<ul>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant -v</code> â€“ get the vagrant version</li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant status</code> â€“ outputs status of the vagrant machine</li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant global-status</code> â€“ outputs status of all vagrant machines</li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant global-status</code> â€“prune â€“ same as above, but prunes invalid entries</li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant provision --debug</code> â€“ use the debug flag to increase the verbosity of the output</li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant push</code> â€“ yes, vagrant can be configured to deploy code!</li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vagrant up --provision | tee provision.log</code> â€“ Runs vagrant up, forces provisioning and logs all output to a file</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="plugins">Plugins</h3>
<p><a href="https://github.com/cogitatio/vagrant-hostsupdater">vagrant-hostsupdater</a>: <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">$ vagrant plugin install vagrant-hostsupdater</code> to update your /etc/hosts file automatically each time you start/stop your vagrant box.</p>

